      "text": "Well, you have to go back a bit to find out what a war actually is."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "9d29f5a8084f4f21",
      "text": "A war is a [[Conflict]]. So what applies to all conflicts also applies to wars. And the best way to define what a conflict is in terms of communication theory is that there are at least two parties, usually reduced to two parties in the course of the conflict because everyone somewhere views their fellow human beings or their environment - what do I know - according to the motto whoever is not for me is for me, so at some point you have to take a stand, as you can now see in the Ukraine-Russia conflict. A conflict is therefore an interaction or communication between two parties who deny each other's claims."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8967c80c4f693e7f",
      "text": "So let's take a banal conflict that probably everyone knows: a conflict in a couple dynamic. He says let's go to the movies and she says no let's go out for dinner yes to bring it down to a very flat level and if then says no let's go to the movies, no let's go out for dinner no then they get into a [[Oscillation]] between two positions. And there's no reason to stop as long as everyone insists on their position. yes, what distinguishes war from other conflicts that everyone knows is that it's a matter of life and death. So the fact that one party threatens the other in such a way that their survival is endangered is what distinguishes wars from other conflicts."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "8010685c199e862a",
      "text": "These conflicts can be resolved if we stick to the couple relationship yes then the one who kills the other wins yes because that's the only way to stay otherwise you have to rely on the other going to the movies well let's go out to eat. If he uses violence then they won't have much fun at dinner or at the movies and that may go on for a while but of course that's usually not the end of the conflict but at some point you get paid back so now let's leave aside the banal marital or couple conflict and look at real serious wars."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "18dfb961854a78f4",
      "text": "If you look at history, wars always end when someone draws the white flag. World War II ended when the Germans surrendered on May 8 and later when the Japanese surrendered; [[surrender]] means I accept the relationship between a winner and a loser, but relationship definitions always require the consent of both yes, so that means you can't unilaterally determine what a relationship is like, you can keep someone under your thumb and bludgeon them, but if you try to do that then you have to make a lot of effort because the moment you drop the threat of violence or the violence becomes less, the resistance immediately becomes great and you terminate the relationship. Yes, that means if you look at wars that have not ended in surrender, the Balkans for example, where we have had conflicts for centuries, or in Northern Ireland, the weaker party that doesn't surrender may stop fighting for a while, but that's just to gather strength. When the right moment comes, they will strike again."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "35b66e720453ff8a",
      "text": "That means such wars don't end, they become latent somehow. Yes, that means you give up for a while until the opportunity arises again. That means that in the long term you can only achieve [[Peace]] if both parties say yes to it in good conscience. So everyone has a right of veto over peace. That's why you can start a war at any time. Yes, for example, if you have an asymmetrical relationship: one is the big one, the other is the small one, and then the small one always has the chance to enter into a symmetrical relationship by simply declaring war on the big one, breaking his windows or throwing bombs or something like that."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "4bdc6c1fe0cee414",
      "text": "That means [[Peace]] is always tied to both sides saying yes and therefore in a war it is always the weaker party, the loser or the one who accepts this role, who decides that the war is over. And if he doesn't accept it, then the war is not over. That's why the Russians have little chance of winning the war in Ukraine now, because no matter how much they want to arm themselves, they can't control 44 million people. In other words, you have to set up a kind of North Korea 2.0, close all borders and somehow restrict the freedom of all people so that the economy goes to zero and so on. Control doesn't work either and it's simply economic madness and doesn't work, so ultimately the problem with most wars is that those who start them don't think about how they can end them. Because they think, ha, the other side will give in and pull up the white flag. We've seen that now, even if some Russian agencies accidentally published the victory announcements after three days because they had prepared them but weren't prepared for the fact that Ukraine was in no way ready to raise the white flag."
